A Non-Comprehensive Guide to Low-Level Concepts

6 steps
In Progress

This guide serves as an introductory exploration into the complex world of low-level concepts in programming. It's designed to offer a simplified yet thorough understanding of key topics such as memory management, stack and heap, pointers, and more. These fundamental concepts are the building blocks of many programming languages, including Rust, and gaining a grasp on them can greatly enhance your programming skills and capabilities.

Learning Outcomes

  • Understand and explain the basic principles of memory management and how different programming languages approach this task.
  • Differentiate between stack and heap memory, and understand their unique characteristics and uses.
  • Understand what pointers are and their purpose
  • Identify and explain common programming issues such as race conditions and memory leaks
  • Be prepared to learn the ownership system

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Importance of this tutorial

    Before diving into Rust's ownership system, it's crucial to understand a few low-level concepts first:

    1. Memory Management: In most programming languages, the system's memory is managed through either a garbage collector or manual allocation and deallocation of memory blocks. Rust, however, uses a third approach with its ownership system to manage memory, aiming to make your programs more efficient and safe.
    2. Stack and Heap: The stack and the heap are parts of memory available to your code at runtime. The stack stores values in the order it gets them and removes the values in the opposite order. This is referred to as last-in, first-out. The heap, on the other hand, stores data that we don’t know the size of at compile time, or a size that might change.
    3. Pointers: A pointer is a variable that holds a memory address. This could be the address of another variable or any piece of program data. The pointers in Rust are similar to those in other languages, but with additional compile-time checks that prevent errors like null or dangling pointers.
    4. Null and Dangling Pointers: Null pointers are pointers that don't point to any value. Dangling pointers, on the other hand, are pointers that reference a location in memory that may have been given to someone else to use by freeing some memory while preserving a pointer to that memory.

       

    By understanding these concepts, you can better comprehend how Rust's ownership system works and why it's a key feature of the language.

  • Step 2: Explaining Memory

    To start, we need to define what memory is and how memory is laid out while we manipulate data in our program.

    When we create data, modify data, or delete data during a program execution, memory is written and stored in RAM. Depending on the kind of memory, it is either allocated on the stack or on the heap.

    The stack and the heap are not the same thing. The stack is ordered data while the heap is unordered data. They are designed this way because of the kind of data they have. A data is information that either has a known or unknown size. Some data are fixed in size. Others will grow or shrink during program execution. Fixed size data is better stored on the stack. Dynamic sized data is stored on the heap.

    Dynamic sized data poses problems since we can’t know when they will grow or shrink during a program execution. Data on the heap is unordered as well because data can be created or destroyed at different places at the same unknown time.

    To ease this inefficiency, allocated memory contains an address of where it is in the region of memory. This address is then stored in the stack in a Last In First Out manner (LIFO) since an address is fixed size.

    Think of a stack like a stack of plates and each plate contains printed addresses that points to the data somewhere on the heap. This also ensures that the last address pushed into the stack will be the first address to be freed of used memory. This makes it easy to keep track of what part of the heap is used so that it is easy to clean up after it’s used.

    Programming languages use different techniques to track data allocated on the heap and store these addresses on the stack e.g. garbage collector, pointers with manual memory management.

  • Step 3: What are pointers and addresses?

    We have not explained what pointers are and its importance to understand better the ownership system.

    In the context of low-level programming, pointers play a significant role. They are variables that hold a memory address. This address could represent the location of another variable or any piece of program data. When we talk about 'pointing to data', we are referring to a pointer holding the memory address of that data. This allows us to directly access and manipulate the data stored at that specific location in memory.

    Addresses, on the other hand, are unique identifiers for locations in memory. When you declare a variable in your program, the system assigns it an address in the memory where the value of that variable is to be stored. This address can then be accessed or manipulated using pointers.

    For further understanding, this diagram below illustrates the relationship between variables, memory addresses, and pointers. A variable stores a value and is assigned a memory address. This memory address can be accessed by a pointer, which points to the value stored by the variable.

    What about references?

    It's also important to mention 'references'. A reference, like a pointer, is a sort of 'alias' for a piece of data. However, unlike pointers, references are safer and easier to use. In Rust, references are used to borrow ownership of a value, and they are always valid, eliminating the possibility of null or dangling references.

    Although, we hear a lot about ownership, please be patient as they will be explained a lot better in the next tutorial.

  • Step 4: What are memory safety issues?

    Memory-safety issues refer to common types of errors in programming that involve the incorrect handling of memory. These can include race conditions, where two processes access shared data simultaneously, leading to unpredictable outcomes; double free errors, which occur when a program tries to free a memory block that has already been freed; memory leaks, where memory resources are allocated but not freed when no longer needed, leading to increased memory usage over time; and null and dangling pointers, which refer to pointers that do not point to any value or that point to a memory location that has been deallocated, both of which can lead to errors or undefined behavior in a program.

  • Step 5: What are memory safety issues Rust tries to prevent?

    Here are some of the memory safety issues Rust tries to prevent.

    Race Conditions

    A race condition occurs when two or more threads can access shared data and they try to change it at the same time. As a result, the values of variables may be unpredictable and vary depending on the timings of context switches of the processes. The diagram below explains how this happens.

    Each thread is a process and as each process is trying to access and modify the same data at the same time, this leads to a race condition.

    Double Free

    Double free error occurs when a program tries to free a block of memory that has already been freed. This can lead to program crashes or unexpected behavior because once a block of memory is freed, the program could reallocate that block to another pointer. Then, if the program tries to free the original pointer again, it's also freeing the memory that's now referenced by the second pointer, which can lead to that pointer's data being unexpectedly modified or to other undefined behavior.

    Dangling Pointers

    Dangling pointers are pointers that point to a memory location that has been freed or deallocated. They occur when the object they point to is deleted or deallocated, without modifying the value of the pointer, hence it still points to the memory location of the deallocated memory. As a result, the dangling pointer is pointing to a location that is no longer valid, and trying to access it can lead to undefined behavior or errors in the program.

    Null Pointers

    Null pointers are pointers that do not point to any value. They can be dangerous because attempting to access such pointers can lead to undefined behavior, such as crashes or corrupt data. In some languages, null pointers are used to signify that there is no data, but this can lead to null pointer dereference errors if not handled correctly.

    Rust prevents null pointers by using the Option data type for values that might not exist. When you try to access the value, Rust forces you to handle the case where it might be None (i.e., null). This way, Rust ensures that you're explicitly handling these cases, preventing null pointer errors.

  • Step 6: Conclusion

    In conclusion, understanding these low-level concepts is crucial for writing efficient and error-free code in Rust and many other languages. The concepts of memory management, stack and heap, pointers, and potential issues like race conditions, double free errors, memory leaks, null and dangling pointers all play a significant role in how we structure and optimize our programs.

    By being aware of these, you can leverage Rust's strengths and its ownership system to write safe, efficient code that is free from common bugs associated with low-level operations. Remember, mastering these concepts takes practice, so keep exploring and experimenting.

    Let's continue to the next tutorial about Rust's ownership system.
